T1  - Specific and ad valorem tariffs are not equivalent in trade wars
AU  - Lockwood, Ben
AU  - Wong, Kar-yiu
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 52
IS  - 1
SP  - 183
EP  - 195
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(99)00053-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199699000537
KW  - Equivalence between specific and ad valorem tariffs
KW  - Trade war
AB  - This note argues that when two countries choose optimal tariffs in a trade war, specific tariffs are not equivalent to ad valorem tariffs even if all markets are competitive. In particular, it shows that if a country’s trading partner switches from a specific tariff to an ad valorem tariff that yields the same revenue at the initial trade point, the former country has an incentive to lower its tariff. When two identical countries choose the types and magnitudes of tariffs in a two-stage game, they will choose ad valorem tariffs, making the trade war less severe.
ER  - 

